Objective

We are provided a simulated dataset with customer loan history/profile along with whether they defaulted or not. We want to create a model to predict the probability of default using the given variables:

Details
• fgood: Default (0), Not Default (1).
• cbs1: Credit score 1.
• cbs2: Credit score 2.
• cbs3: Credit score 3.
• cbinq: Number of inquiries.
• cbline: Number of credit lines.
• cbterm: Number of term loans.
• cblineut: Line utilization (0-100).
• cbtob: Number of years on file.
• cbdpd: Indicator of days past due on bureau (Yes, No).
• cbnew: Number of new loans. !<<<<<this is actually not number of new loans>>>>>>!
• pmt: Type of payment (M: Manual, A: Autopay, P: Payroll).
• tob: Time on books (Years).
• dpd: Level of delinquency (No, Low, High).
• dep: Amount of deposits own by customer.
• dc: Number of debit card transactions.
• od: Number of overdrafts.
• home: Home ownership indicator (Yes, No).
• inc: Level of income.
• dd: Number of direct deposits per month.
• online: Indicator of active online (Yes, No).
• rnd: Random number to select testing and training samples.
• period: Factor that indicates the year/month of the data.
creditData <- read_csv('CreditData.csv', show_col_types = FALSE)

Looking at the above plot suggests that the missing income values should be their own class, as NAs represent almost 10% of the data, and the ratio of default to not default is not unlike the rest of the classes. So, replacing NAs with the mode does not make sense. For the sake of curiosity, let’s explore what happens if we remove it (i.e., applying list-wise deletion).

Dropping the rows of these missing values (which only appear in the income column) does not appear to introduce bias. Comparing the summary statistics of df0 and df for the categorical variable also suggests that the missing data might have been Missing at Random (MAR)

As the subset (with missing inc values) of data is representative of the original sample, an list-wise deletion of these rows would not introduce bias to our original data. That is to say, the missing data is “missing completely at random.” However, given that it represents 10% of our data (which is actually more than 5 other classes of income), removing it would lead to loss of predictive power or efficiency.

Feature Importance

Now, we want to identify which features affect our target variable fgood. For that, we use risk ratios. So, we will look at the default rate within each group. This will give us an intuition into which variables and groups are important in predicting default.

# see the rmd for the code
for (chunk in plot_chunks) {
  combined_plot <- wrap_plots(chunk, ncol = 2, nrow = 2) & 
    plot_annotation(caption = "Risk ratios in red text") &
    theme(plot.caption = element_text(color='red'))
  print(combined_plot)
}

For each factor, if the difference diff (class default rate minus global default rate) in a class is positive then those that are in that class are more likely to default. When the risk ratio is greater than 1, those with that class are more likely to default; when less than 1, less likely and if it’s close to 1, the class likely does not affect default rate. If we don’t see any variation among the classes in a factor, then this suggests that factor is not an important feature in predicting default; for instance, this look like the case for online.

We make a few more observations:

  • Having no credit line corresponds to being half as likely to default, while having at least three increases the likelyhood of defaulting.
  • No credit inquiries implies being half as likely to default than average, while those with two hard inquiries are twice as likely than average to default.
  • As for term loans, including mortgages, auto loans, personal installment loans, and student loans, having two increases the chances of default, while having just one doesn’t seem to influence default probability. On the other hand, those with no term loans are 40% less likely to default.
  • In our data, credit history (on bureau) cbtob ranges from 3 to 8 (inclusive). Those with 8 years are half as less likely to default, and the likelihood to default decreases with the number of years, with those having just 3 years of history being twice as likely to default on average.
  • If they are past due on bureau, they are twice as likely to default, though the opposite doesn’t seem to have any bearing on the future.
  • At the time of application, applicants with no credit cbnew history are 75% more likely to default than average.
  • Those that use Payroll for payments default at 6% rate, making them roughly 70% less likely to default, while those that pay manually are 50% more likely and automatic payment corresponds to being 50% less likely to default.
  • tob - the number of years with the current financial institution ranges from 0 to 5. Those that are new are 3 times likely to default than average. This decreases with tenure, with those having tenure of 4, 5 years defaulting below 5%.
  • As expected, level of delinquency is a good predictor, same with home ownership showing a wide margin contrast
  • While having 0 overdraft implies a 30% less likelihood of defaulting, having one doesn’t seem to affect probability of defaulting, but having two increases default rate by 73%


Now, let’s explore the continuous features.

To make interpretations clearer, we make the decision to introduce a default column from fgood. If fgood is zero, it means they defaulted (1). We also leave it as a numeric 0, 1 for correlation calculation.

df$default <- as.numeric(df$fgood == 0)

Now, observe the correlation among the continuous features and default.

M <- cor(keep(df, is.numeric))
corrplot(M, method='shade', type='upper', order='AOE', diag=0, addCoef.col='darkgreen')

The more money they have in their deposit account, the less likely they are to default. Similarly, as one would expect, having a higher credit score cbs is negatively correlated with defaulting, similarly for the number of debt card transactions dc. On the other hand, the credit utilization ratio cblineut is moderately (positively) correlated with defaulting. Roughly speaking, the more the higher the credit utilization ratio cblineut, the more likely they are to default.

Four out of five own a home, have no term loans, and all have been on the bureau’s file for at least 5 years. None of them has days past due on the bureau either. These could truly be outliers or individuals who faced fraud/identity theft, income shock or business/investment failure. It is not reasonable to remove them since these circumstances, though unpredictable, are still things that happen in real life; it would make our model be biased towards predicting only typical behavior.


Now, let’s look at credit line utilization. This is a quantity calculated as percentage of total outstanding balance to total credit limit. It is generally suggested to limit it to no more than 30%.

Model Construction (Baseline Model)

First, let’s make a baseline model. Logistic Regression is a good candidate. Recall the assumptions:

  1. Pairwise linear relationship between the logit of the target and each feature
    • \(\operatorname{logit}(p) = \log(p/(1-p))\) where \(p\) predicted probabilities of the target
  2. No significant multicollinearity among the features (we will perform GVIF/VIF later on)
  3. The observations are independent

Since the categorical columns are stored as factors, R will do hot-encoding for them automatically

There is fgood and default. We will keep default as a target variable

df0 <- df %>% select(-fgood) 
# split the data into training and test set. 
set.seed(123)
training_samples <- df0$default %>%
  createDataPartition(p=0.8, list=FALSE)
trainData <- df0[training_samples, ]
testData <- df0[-training_samples, ]

Performance Metrics

We are interested in the False Negatives, i.e., predicted 0 (not default), but actual 1 (defaulted). In other words, those that were predicted to not default, but actually defaulted. These present huge financial risk to the creditor, so we want to capture them as much as possible. Additionally, since there is a class bias, the accuracy can be misleading, i.e., when 80% of the individuals are defaulting, it is not surprising that a model gets ~80% (accuracy) or more right.

Since we would like to minimize False Negatives, we want to minimize FN/(FN+TP), that is, maximize Sensitivity = TP/(FN+TP) aka True Positive Rate. The model we have right now has sensitivity (TPR) that is quite low at 44%, and so is the precision (Positive Predicted Balue) sitting in at 66%, while Specificity is quite high 94 (good).

So, we have to test different probability cutoffs to improve sensitivity and precision. Going forward, we will use the stepwise logistic reg. model that we trained for comparision

probabilities <- probabilities_step
model <- step_model

Our model now has 79.6% accuracy, but the sensitivity is 85.5%, we have an increase of True Positives and decrease of False Negatives; kappa also jumped to 51% from 48%. By losing out on specificity, we are rejecting more borrowers that would have not defaulted, but since we are predicting default, one could say it is less riskier this way as there is a significant improvement of sensitivity. We want to see if we can further tune the model to strike a good balance between specificity and sensitivity (i.e., if we could lift the ROC to get a better AUC).

Note that since we are using robust performance metrics (ROC curve, recall, precision, kappa), we are effectively dealing with the class imbalance (of having 80% no default to 20% of default), but alternatively, we could have also used SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling) from the DMwR library to resample our training data and mitigate the class imbalance.

Some more feature engineering

We prepare helper functions to efficiently compare the models and parameters

# a function to train a model and return the model along with probabilities
generateModel <- function(dataF, features) {   # features as a vector, requires `caret` and `pROC`
  set.seed(123)
  training_samples <- dataF$default %>%
    createDataPartition(p=0.8, list=FALSE)
  trainData <- dataF[training_samples, ]
  testData <- dataF[-training_samples, ]
  
  formula <- as.formula(paste("default ~ ", paste(features, collapse = " + ")))
  gen_model <- glm(formula, data=dataF, family=binomial)
  probabilities <- gen_model %>% predict(testData, type = 'response') 
  
  return(
    list(
      model = gen_model, 
      probs = probabilities, 
      obsclass = testData$default # these are observed classes
    )
  )
}

# a function to plot the ROC curve
plotROC <- function(observedClasses, probabilities) {
  resRoc <- roc(observedClasses, probabilities)
  plot.roc(resRoc, print.auc=TRUE, print.thres='best')
}

# a function to generate the confusion matrix
generateConfMatrix <- function(prob_cutoff, prob, observedClasses){
  predictedClasses <- ifelse(prob>prob_cutoff, 1, 0)
  result <- caret::confusionMatrix(factor(predictedClasses), factor(observedClasses),positive='1')
  return(result)
}

# a function to convert factors to numeric: 
# as.numeric would normally convert say `00` to 1 since it's the 
# first level and we would like to avoid those scenarios
tonumeric <- function(cell) {
  return(as.numeric(as.character(cell)))
} #only apply to those with 00, 01, 02, etc levels, not booleans or inc

Let’s create some new more variables/features. These could potentially be correlated, and we will drop them after performing vif.

We achieve an improved AUC, kappa and a reasonable trade-off between Sensitivity and Specificity. We can interpret the coefficients in the following way. For instance, take dpd1.

odds_ratios['incW04'] # level of delinquency
##   incW04 
## 1.817824

This is the increased odds (1.818) that a borrower with income rating of 4 will default relative to a borrower with an income rating of 1 (baseline W01) while holding other factors constant. So, those with income ratings of 4 are more likely to default than those of 1. This is similar to the risk ratio analysis we did in the Exploratory Data Analysis section.

An odds ratio that is above 1 represents an increase in the odds of the event, whereas a ratio of less than 1 implies a decrease. So, for instance,

odds_ratios['avg_cred_line']
## avg_cred_line 
##     0.5912222

This implies that, assuming all other predictors are held constant, for one unit increase in avg_cred_line (average credit line), which we defined as the ratio of the number of credit lines to the number of years on file, the odds of a borrower defaulting decreases by a factor of 0.6 (or 40%). This could be explained by perhaps the event that a higher average credit line indicates that lenders have deemed teh borrower creditworthy enough to extend more credit, or having above average financial stability.

Conclusion

The top contributing features appear to be the credit score, amount of deposits owned by the customer, history of delinquency (Low, High), and type of payment (Manual). See Exploratory Data Analysis

Though less important than reducing risk by increasing sensitivity/precision, ideally we would also want a high as possible specificity (percentage of non-defaulters identified properly) so long as we don’t lose on sensitivity; this is because, if possible, we would not want to lose out on borrowers who would have been able to pay off the loan by rejecting them as they would be a source of interest revenue for the creditor. So, we have a choice of two models based on whether we want to be extremely risk-averse (choosing the model with 85% sensitivity) or strike a balance to capture the aforementioned types of borrowers by marginally improving specificity (the last model with 83-81:sensitivity to specificity).

Weaknesses / Suggested Improvements

  • Take a look at Cook’s Distance, and in-depth Residual Analysis to deal with outliers and take a closer look at those ‘outliers’. On initial assessment (see accompanying scripts), we could see a number of influential points (from top 5 Cook’s distance values) that included customers who had zero years on credit bureau file with high dep that did not default; removing these would not be ideal, but if they were removed, it would shift the logistic regression S-curve. As a result, the decision was that outliers unless arising from observation/record error are important in our problem of predicting default unless a deeper analysis was conducted on these cases.

  • Effect of having no credit scores. When it’s missing or say we put 0, what happens? Regression analysis?

  • Compare performance with other binary classfiers.
